		</item>
		<item>
		<title>Negotiate Up!</title>
		<link>http://www.adsalestips.com/negotiate-up/</link>
		<comments>http://www.adsalestips.com/negotiate-up/#respond</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 28 Feb 2014 13:32:20 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[morris]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.adsalestips.com/?p=2397</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[I consider myself a pretty good sales person, however by nature I have a tendency to try and please my advertisers, which means I say ‘yes’ [&#8230;]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I consider myself a pretty good sales person, however by nature I have a tendency to try and please my advertisers, which means I say ‘yes’ too easily: I need some tips on Negotiating please?</p>
<p>Tip: In my experience you can be an amazing sales person but a poor negotiator. It is a fact that all the top media agencies send their media buyers to negotiation courses, therefore in order to level the playing field we, as sales people, also need to have training on negotiating.Let me give you a tip: We all have a rate card, if the customer says the rate is too high and starts talking about the CPT, your first instinct needs to be to handle it as an objection and start to negotiate up, not down. If the client also showed an interest in web, digital, newsletters, editorial or double pages over single page adverts, these can all be used a variables. Preserve the rate amount by using your bag of variables as added value, the client might be very interested to send out an exclusive newsletter or take a banner advert on your website or run a double page over a single page, use these variables to bolster the package and maintain the dollar amount.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://www.adsalestips.com/negotiate-up/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		</item>
		<item>
		<title>Taking time to make appointments</title>
		<link>http://www.adsalestips.com/taking-time-to-make-appointments/</link>
		<comments>http://www.adsalestips.com/taking-time-to-make-appointments/#respond</comments>
		<pubDate>Wed, 12 Feb 2014 13:31:11 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[morris]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.adsalestips.com/?p=2395</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[I have recently been promoted from classified sales to selling display advertising, this means I must have a minim of 10 face to face meeting per [&#8230;]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I have recently been promoted from classified sales to selling display advertising, this means I must have a minim of 10 face to face meeting per week, I am struggling in my first month to get 5 appointments and my conversation rate is very poor, when I sold classified I was very good at getting prospects to buy over the phone, now that I have to meet clients and agencies something is not working, what am I doing wrong?</p>
<p>Tips: Sounds to me that you are experiencing a problem with the quality of your appointments, let me help. Advertisers and agency people are often very busy and the harsh truth is they often stick to what &#038; who they know that works and is comfortable; buying from your competition, or buying less than they should, until you get the opportunity to meet them you are unable begin to persuade them to consider new and alternative ideas. Unlike many sales directors I prefer quality appointments over quantity, which means I have the decision maker in front of me, I am clear on my goals and objectives behind the meeting, today my conversation rate is around 90% for that reason I ‘structure time to get appointments’</p>
<p>A sales person or sales assistant making appointments must come in every morning with a goal of contacting sufficient prospects to reach the desired quality of appointments in a week, decide on which area or which client group you intend to target and stick at it for as long as it takes until you have succeed to fix the desired amount of appointments, if a prospect asks you to call back, ask them when would be convenient and make sure to call them back at the that exact time.</p>
<p>Have a list of calls you wish to make every morning, this is the key, do not waste time thinking about who you should call, at the end of each day before you go home have your list of calls on your desk or computer for the following morning, this helps keep clarity in your mind plus a clear objective for your appointment fixing in addition, sales people can make it even easier to create momentum if they send an appointment request email the night before so that in the morning you should have some replies to work on when you get into the office. Remember, if you are making appointments for yourself or for your sales director, the quality of that appointment makes all the difference to being effective and bring home the bacon.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://www.adsalestips.com/taking-time-to-make-appointments/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		</item>
		<item>
		<title>Phone sales tips</title>
		<link>http://www.adsalestips.com/phone-sales-tips/</link>
		<comments>http://www.adsalestips.com/phone-sales-tips/#respond</comments>
		<pubDate>Thu, 06 Feb 2014 13:29:28 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[morris]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.adsalestips.com/?p=2393</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[From a user: I graduated last year in business studies and I’ve been trying to get a job with very little success. Last month I started [&#8230;]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><strong>From a user:</strong><br />
I graduated last year in business studies and I’ve been trying to get a job with very little success. Last month I started working for a small publishing company in London that gave me a one hour product training and a telephone; I wanted to resign that very same day but instead I thought: why not use this for experience, give it 100% and see where it all ends up. I went online to find some advertising sales advise and came across this site and subscribed to the sales process course which was a real eye opener: the company I work for does not believe in face-to-face calls, I am unable to send out a copy of the magazine, I can only make 60 calls per day and send out my media kit by email. I need some telephone sales tips please?</p>
<p><strong>Tips:</strong><br />
Do not panic, help is here. I actually started my career when I was 17 in telesales, it can actually be fun and a real buzz; on the telephone you can be whatever you want, picture yourself a tall confident person, determined and powerful.<br />
&#8211; Each day start with a positive attitude<br />
&#8211; Learn your pitch back to front, know everything there is to know about your title and industry<br />
&#8211; Identify 60 contact calls each day, before going home each evening, move across the calls that you could not reach and add the difference, always start the day with 60 names to call<br />
&#8211; Keep an agenda clean and organized, when prospect asks you to call back, make a note when to call back and then call them back<br />
&#8211; As you are starting out, go online and read about DIPADA OR AIDA steps, super basic but this will help you get started<br />
Whether you are selling face-to-face or over the telephone the same principles apply. The key is, when you get someone on the phone make sure the first thing you say will catch their attention and interest, then ask some quick open questions to make sure you are on track and present your unique selling points; finally, before you end the call, ask the prospect if they have an interest and then try and trail close to test the water. Whatever you do, never read from a script, telephone sales is 80% about using your sunny personality to the point they can even hear your smile on the phone.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://www.adsalestips.com/phone-sales-tips/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
